The George Brown College offers a Human Resources program (B154) within its School of Human Resources that enables students to learn how to design human resources policies and programs, attract and retain a productive workforce, manage employee diversity, ensure health and safety at the workplace, and advise on employee/labour relations. Students can work towards obtaining professional designations through the Human Resources Professional Association of Ontario (HRPA). This program is accredited by the Accreditation Council for Business Schools and Programs (ACBSP), and students are required to bring their own laptops due to George Brown's Bring Your Own Device (BYOD) initiative. The human resources program requires the completion of two semesters of work term experience, which can be co-op (paid) or internship (unpaid). Students are encouraged to pursue self-directed industry work experience opportunities as well. For more information, contact the Centre for Business at business@georgebrown.ca.

The George Brown College offers a three-year Business Administration – Human Resources advanced diploma program. International students are not eligible for optional co-op arrangements. Graduates of this program can find employment in various positions such as human resources coordinator, human resources assistant, human resources specialist, human resources administrator, and recruitment coordinator. For students wishing to pursue an optional Training and Development stream, they may apply courses towards the Certified Training and Development Professional (CTDP) designation. Students with a minimum overall grade point average of 3.0 or higher are eligible for block transfer admission into semester 5 of the Human Resources Strategy and Technology degree program at Seneca College. To graduate from the program, students need to complete 37 courses: 30 mandatory courses, 4 business electives, 3 general education electives, and 2 work experience terms (which can be co-op, internship, simulation, consulting or research projects). Some students may be required to take COMM 1000 (Introduction to College Communication) before progressing to COMM 2000. Similarly, they may be required to take MATH 1027 (Business Math with Remediation) before progressing to MATH 1008. However, these courses do not count towards the total number of required courses. There is also a transfer guide available for information on additional future study options. The Centre for Business provides field education opportunities. For more information on international students and optional co-op arrangements, please consult with the international student office.

The Payroll Practitioner Stream is a program offered by the college where students can gain additional knowledge and practical experience in payroll administration. Upon completion, students may pursue the Payroll Compliance Practitioner (PCP) designation through the National Payroll Institute (NPI). The Payroll Practitioner Stream includes the following semester courses with their respective codes, minimum grades, pre-requisites, and additional costs:

1. BUS 1084 - Payroll Compliance Legislation (additional cost required)
2. BUS 1085 - Payroll Fundamentals 1 (additional cost required)
3. BUS 1086 - Payroll Fundamentals 2 (additional cost required)

For General Education Electives, students can choose from Business Elective Courses for Business Administration – Human Resources, including:

1. BUS 1044 - Business Law (none)
2. COMP 1113 - Principles of E-Business
3. COMP 1010 - Business Computer Applications I and II
4. CMMK 1127 - The Business Media in Canada
5. COMM 1034 - Talking Business
6. HRM 2028 - Training Design & Delivery** (by interview only)
7. HRM 2002 and HRM 3005 - International Human Resources Management
8. MARK 2053 - Negotiation Skills (none)
9. HRM 2030 - Field Based Advanced Coaching (by interview only)
10. MGMT 4009 - Operations Management
11. MATH 1008 - Calculus I
12. BUS 3015 - Applied Business Planning
13. ACCT 2031, MARK 1020, MATH 1008, and HRM 1030 - Business Research & Report Writing
14. MGMT 2026 - The Successful Project Manager
15. BUS 1040 and COMP 1115 - (none)
16. BUS 1086 - Payroll Fundamentals 2 (additional cost required)
17. ECON 1031 and ECON 1032 - Microeconomics and Macroeconomics (none)

* The courses marked with an asterisk (*) require additional costs through the National Payroll Institute.
** HRM 2028 and HRM 2027 have a pre-requisite of an interview only.

The graduate from this program will be able to demonstrate the ability to:

1. Understand and apply payroll compliance legislation
2. Process and manage various types of employee records, benefits, and payroll information
3. Utilize computer applications in processing and maintaining payroll information
4. Understand the principles of business law as it applies to human resources management
5. Apply effective communication skills in a business setting
6. Design and deliver training programs
7. Develop an international perspective on human resources management
8. Conduct effective negotiations
9. Provide advanced coaching in a field setting
10. Analyze organizational performance data and use it to improve operations
11. Plan, organize, and manage projects efficiently and effectively
12. Apply microeconomic principles to business situations
13. Understand macroeconomic trends and their impact on businesses.

8. MARK 2053 - Negotiation Skills (none)

11. MATH 1008 - Calculus I
12. BUS 3015 - Applied Business Planning

14. MGMT 2026 - The Successful Project Manager
15. BUS 1040 and COMP 1115 - (none)
16. BUS 1086 - Payroll Fundamentals 2 (additional cost required)

1. Understand and apply payroll compliance legislation

3. Utilize computer applications in processing and maintaining payroll information
4. Understand the principles of business law as it applies to human resources management
5. Apply effective communication skills in a business setting
6. Design and deliver training programs
7. Develop an international perspective on human resources management
8. Conduct effective negotiations
9. Provide advanced coaching in a field setting
10. Analyze organizational performance data and use it to improve operations
11. Plan, organize, and manage projects efficiently and effectively
12. Apply microeconomic principles to business situations
13. Understand macroeconomic trends and their impact on businesses.
